      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During the time of redlining, there were several sociological and pseudo-scientific theories that attempted to justify segregation and maintain racial homogeneity. One example is the \"Fundamental Law of Human Nature\" theory, which posited that humans are inherently divided into distinct racial groups with unique characteristics, needs, and abilities. This theory was often used to argue that segregation was necessary to preserve the social and psychological stability of each racial group. For instance, some proponents of segregation claimed that African Americans were more prone to crime and violence due to their supposedly \"primitive\" and \"savage\" nature, and that separating them from white communities was necessary to protect white children from the perceived dangers of racial mixing.\n\nAnother example is the \"Social Distance Theory\", which was developed by sociologists such as Lothrop Stoddard and Charles Goddard. This theory posited that humans have an innate tendency to maintain social distance from members of other racial groups, and that segregation was necessary to preserve this social distance and maintain racial harmony. By separating neighborhoods, proponents claimed that racial groups could maintain their own social structures and avoid the perceived stresses and strains of racial mixing.\n\nThese theories, while discredited by modern scholars, were used to justify segregation and redlining during the",
